    • default colors are easier to perceive by people with a variety of color blindness conditions

### - removing the planets discovered by those methods (with fewer than 50 exoplanet  discoveries)
over_50_methods = planets %>%
  group_by(method) %>%
  summarize(count = n())%>%
  filter(count >= 50)

methods = semi_join(planets, over_50_methods)

methods_total = methods %>%
  select(year,method)%>%
  group_by(year)%>%
  summarize(total = n())


methods_groups= methods %>%
  count(year,method)

final_methods = full_join(methods_groups,methods_total)

final_methods = final_methods%>%
  mutate(proportion = n /total)%>%
  arrange(year)%>%
  select(-total)

total_prcp = official %>% 
  select(date, prcp)%>% 
  drop_na()%>% 
  mutate(year = year(date),
         month = month(date, label = TRUE),
         day = day(date)) %>% 
  count(month)%>% 
  rename(total_precipitation = n)

positive_prcp = official %>% 
  select(date, prcp)%>% 
  drop_na()%>% 
  mutate(year = year(date),
         month = month(date, label = TRUE),
         day = day(date)) %>% 
  filter(prcp>0) %>% 
  count(month)

  • 6c. The average temperature (mean of tavg) by month for the years from 1991-2020. Consider these values to be the current normal mean temperatures. Then, find the average temperature by month in 2022. In how many months was the average temperature in 2022 higher than the normal mean temperature?
q6c_91_20_df = official%>%
  select(date, tavg) %>%
  drop_na()%>% 
  mutate(year = year(date),
         month = month(date, label = TRUE)) %>% 
  filter(year>=1991 & year<=2020)   %>% 
  group_by(year)%>% 
  group_by(month)%>% 
  summarize(avg_temp_in_91_20 = mean(tavg))


q6c_22_df = official%>%
  select(date, tavg) %>%
  drop_na()%>% 
  mutate(year = year(date),
         month = month(date, label = TRUE)) %>% 
  filter(year == 2020)   %>%
  group_by(month)%>%
  summarize(avg_temp_in_2022 = mean(tavg))


q6c_df = left_join(q6c_91_20_df, q6c_22_df, by = 'month')

  1. The mean daily average temperature in Madison in January, 2023 was 27.02 degrees Fahrenheit.
  • Calculate the mean average daily temperature for each January from the official Madison weather data.
  • Create a subset of this data set with the year and mean daily average temperature for the highest 25 of these years, arranged from highest to lowest value. Add an initial column named rank with values from 1 to 25. Print this entire data summary table
  • In terms of mean daily average temperature in January, how does 2023 compare to all previously recorded months in Madison since 1869?
q7_df = official %>%
  select(date,tavg)%>%
  drop_na()%>%
mutate(year = year(date),
         month = month(date, label = TRUE)) %>% 
  filter(month == "Jan")%>% 
  group_by(year)%>% 
  summarize(jan_tavg = mean(tavg))


q7_subdf = q7_df%>%

In terms of mean daily average temperature in January, the recorded average temperature in 2023 is significantly higher than those of previous years, counting from 1869. That said, the average January temperature of 2023, which is 27.02, is only lower than the 7th highest average January temperature. This makes 2023 January temperature higher than approximately 95% of the values in the dataset.

  1. Make a plot which shows the average January temperature in Madison from 1869–2022. Add a smooth trend curve to the plot. Add a red dashed horizontal line at the mean temperature for 2023. Include meaningful axis labels and a title for the plot.
ggplot(q7_df, aes(x=year, y = jan_tavg)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  geom_smooth(se = FALSE) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 27.02, linetype=2, color = "red") +
  xlab("Year") +
  ylab("Average temperature in January") +
  ggtitle("Average January Temperature in Madison over time",
         subtitle = "1869 - 2022")
